<WRITING SEX="FEMALE" PERSON="BRWWRITER"><ORLANDOHEADER TYPE="text"><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><DOCTITLE>Elizabeth Bathurst: writing</DOCTITLE></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><AUTHORITY>Orlando Project</AUTHORITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC>Based on original research by members of the Orlando Project.</SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="SUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>21 June 2010</DATE><ITEM>Initial document given to tagger.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>9 March 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>12 March 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>16 March 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>8 May 2011</DATE><ITEM>cas-ing and tag reports are done, but there are researchnotes that need answering.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>9 May 2011</DATE><ITEM>queries after cas dealt with</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>9 May 2011</DATE><ITEM>answered researchnote</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>11 May 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, rbv c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>31 May 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub i</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>31 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>8 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, pilot42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="pub" RESP="MPO" WORKVALUE="c"><DATE>21 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c, pilot42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Writing</HEADING><STANDARD>Bathurst, Elizabeth</STANDARD><AUTHORSUMMARY><SHORTPROSE><P>EB, writing late in the seventeenth century, was one of the most popular women writers to be published by the <ORGNAME>Sowle Press</ORGNAME>, the best-known <ORGNAME STANDARD="Society of Friends" REG="Quakers">Quaker</ORGNAME> publishing house. <GENERICRANGE><EXTENTOFOEUVRE>Her three publications (dating from a <TGENRE GENRENAME="POLEMIC">period of struggle</TGENRE> for the Quakers) were collected and re-issued after her early death to make up a fourth. They include <TGENRE GENRENAME="THEOLOGY">theological</TGENRE> analysis, <TGENRE GENRENAME="RELIGIOUS">religious</TGENRE> exhortation, and <TGENRE GENRENAME="FEMINIST">feminist</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="ANTHOLOGY">enumeration</TGENRE> of women&apos;s words from the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REND="normal">Bible</TITLE>.</EXTENTOFOEUVRE></GENERICRANGE></P></SHORTPROSE></AUTHORSUMMARY><DIV1><HEADING>Three Publications</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Truth&apos;s Vindication</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66528" PLACEHOLDER="EB, Truth&apos;s Vindication, 1679"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>1679</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EB published a spirited and <TGENRE GENRENAME="THEOLOGY">theologically</TGENRE> learned defence of <TTHEMETOPIC><ORGNAME STANDARD="Society of Friends" REG="Quakers">Quaker</ORGNAME> beliefs and practices</TTHEMETOPIC> which she entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Truth&apos;s Vindication</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The fuller title reads <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Truth&apos;s Vindication">Truth&apos;s Vindication, Or, A Gentle Stroke to wipe off the Foul Aspersions, False Accusations and Misrepresentations, cast upon the People of God called Quakers, both with respect to their Principle, and their way of Proselyting People over to them </TITLE>. <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The title-page carries four texts from the <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC" REG="Bible" REND="normal">Old Testament</TITLE>,</TINTERTEXTUALITY> and flags the inclusion of a shorter work, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">An <TGENRE GENRENAME="EPISTLE">Epistle</TGENRE> to such of the Friends of Christ, that have lately been convinced of the Truth as it is in Jesus</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Truth&apos;s title-page" DBREF="66528">title-page</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PMATERIALCONDITIONS>EB says she began writing this book <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">some time since,</QUOTE> in response to debates which may by now be forgotten. There was so much to say that the work took longer than she had expected and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">swelled beyond my intention.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Truth&apos;s 2" DBREF="66528">2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMATERIALCONDITIONS> <PEDITIONS>Several different re-issues followed in 1683.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ESTC" DBREF="10912"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS></P><P><PAUTHORSHIP AUTHORSHIPCONTROVERSY="SPURIOUS" CONTROVERSYDATE="HISTORICAL">Some people would not believe that this learned book <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">was of [EB&apos;s] own Indicting,</QUOTE> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">because of the meanness or weakness of her Person,</QUOTE></PAUTHORSHIP> but <NAME>George Whitehead</NAME> (widower of <NAME>Anne Whitehead</NAME>) testified that he <PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY>had seen the whole text drafted in her handwriting before it was published,</PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY> and that she had a good understanding of the issues she wrote of.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Truth b4" DBREF="66545">b4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The book opens with several stages of preliminary matter. <PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">In an opening epistle to five individual Friends, EB says she has not acted out of ambition to be printed or to be popular, but in obedience to <NAME>Jesus</NAME>, her Lord.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Truth&apos;s A2" DBREF="66528">A2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The people she is addressing, she says, are her elders in years, but she has felt concerned about stumbling-blocks in the way of their spiritual development, and hopes to be of service to them.</PMOTIVES> In an <TGENRE GENRENAME="INTRODUCTION">introduction</TGENRE> she reiterates that she writes for her former friends and acquaintances who view <TTHEMETOPIC><ORGNAME STANDARD="Society of Friends" REG="Quakers">Quakerism</ORGNAME></TTHEMETOPIC> as a new religion, not understanding that the true religion, which this seeks to be, is very old. Of her new community, the Friends, she writes <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I marvel not that the World hates them, since it hated him (to wit, Christ Jesus) whom they have believed in.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Truth&apos;s B" DBREF="66528">B</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Her book is unusual among women&apos;s writing since it is that of a systematic theologian. Its body is in three parts: a discussion of ten controversial issues including <TTHEMETOPIC>original sin</TTHEMETOPIC>, the <TTHEMETOPIC>body of Christ</TTHEMETOPIC>, <TTHEMETOPIC>free will</TTHEMETOPIC>, and so on; a lengthy, detailed, subdivided description of the <TTHEMETOPIC>principle of truth</TTHEMETOPIC>; and a <TGENRE GENRENAME="POLEMIC">confident <TGENRE GENRENAME="ANSWER">refutation</TGENRE></TGENRE> of various <TTHEMETOPIC>mistakes and errors</TTHEMETOPIC>. Of believers in <TTHEMETOPIC>predestination</TTHEMETOPIC>, says EB, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">being void of universal love themselves, they fondly imagine the Lord to be like themselves.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Truth&apos;s 61" DBREF="66528">61</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TTONESTYLE>Her defence of the Quakers is warm and heartfelt but couched with careful rationality, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">point by theological point.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TTONESTYLE> She draws on her own experience, <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">quotes lavishly from the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REND="normal">Bible</TITLE>,</TINTERTEXTUALITY> and ends by listing printer&apos;s errors in her work. <PATTITUDES>She signs her final statement as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one of the least of the Flock of Christ, whose outward name is Elizabeth Bathurst.</QUOTE></PATTITUDES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Truth&apos;s 104" DBREF="66528">104</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> According to Yasuharu Nakano, EB differed from mainstream Quakerism after the Restoration in that her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">theology centres on the insistence on the <TTHEMETOPIC>sole authority of the Inward Light</TTHEMETOPIC> and on the infallibility of human beings guided by the <TTHEMETOPIC>infallible working of the Spirit</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Nakano 90" DBREF="66627">90</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">In a note in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Quaker Studies</TITLE>, <NAME STANDARD="Nakano, Yasuharu">Nakano</NAME> has compared and distinguished between EB&apos;s <TTHEMETOPIC>soteriology (or doctrine of salvation)</TTHEMETOPIC> and that of <NAME>Robert Barclay</NAME>. He also pointed out that printer&apos;s errors in her works have accumulated from one edition to another <PANTHOLOGIZATION>and into <NAME>Mary Garman</NAME>&apos;s anthology of Quaker women&apos;s writing <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Hidden in Plain Sight: Quaker Women&apos;s Writings, 1650-1700">Hidden in Plain Sight</TITLE>, 1996.</PANTHOLOGIZATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Nakano 99-100" DBREF="66627">90,100</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">An Expostulatory Appeal to the Professors of Christianity</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66527" PLACEHOLDER="EB, An Expostulatory Appeal to the Professors of Christianity, 1680"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1680--" CERTAINTY="UNKNOWN">1680</DATE><CHRONPROSE>This date is generally given to EB&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">An <TGENRE GENRENAME="POLEMIC"><TGENRE GENRENAME="TRACTPAMPHLET">Expostulatory Appeal</TGENRE></TGENRE> to the Professors of Christianity</TITLE>, which appeared some time after Bathurst made a proclamation on <DATE>20 August 1678</DATE>. It stands first in the posthumous volume of her works.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Expostulatory 3" DBREF="66527">3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The fuller title is <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Expostulatory Appeal to the Professors of Christianity, An">An Expostulatory Appeal to the Professors of Christianity, Joyned in Community with <NAME STANDARD="Annesley, Samuel">Samuel Ansley</NAME></TITLE>. EB says she made a proclamation to these people on the twentieth day of the eighth month 1678. At this date <NAME>Samuel Annesley</NAME> (father-in-law of <NAME>John Dunton</NAME>, father of the future <NAME>Susanna Wesley</NAME>) had been for six years ministering to a <TTHEMETOPIC><ORGNAME STANDARD="Presbyterian Church">Presbyterian</ORGNAME>, Calvinist congregation in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="London" REG="Spitalfields">Spitalfields</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG>, London</PLACE>.</TTHEMETOPIC><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Expostulatory 3" DBREF="66527">3</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Annesley" DBREF="29268">under Annesley</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Having been roughly handled by this congregation, EB demands: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Oh! where was your patient Mind . . . . Oh! where was your <EMPH>Christian</EMPH> Moderation . . . . Oh! where was your Lamb-like Meekness.</QUOTE> <TTONESTYLE>She claims her reproof is <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">written in the spirit of Love,</QUOTE> to give an account to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">all sober Inquirers</QUOTE> of the issues at stake between herself and the congregation.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Expostulatory 5" DBREF="66527">5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TTONESTYLE> <PATTITUDES>Having signed her name on page 6, she feels exonerated from further concern with these <TTHEMETOPIC>mistaken believers</TTHEMETOPIC>: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">now having invited you to turn unto the Lord, both by Word and Writing, I am clear concerning you at this time.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Expostulatory 6" DBREF="66527">6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES> <NAME>Anne Bathurst</NAME> (perhaps Elizabeth&apos;s sister, not, it seems, the same <NAME STANDARD="Bathurst, Ann,, c. 1638 - by 1704">Anne or Ann Bathurst</NAME> who was a diarist and associate of <NAME>Jane Lead</NAME>) adds a brief paragraph to similar effect.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Expostulatory 7" DBREF="66527">7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES"><NAME>Charles Marshall</NAME> later wrote that when EB began publishing he <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">was refreshed, and bowed before the great God for his tender Mercies</QUOTE> in perfecting his praise through such a humble instrument.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Truth b7" DBREF="66545">b7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Sayings of Women</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66546" PLACEHOLDER="EB, The Sayings of Women, 1683"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>1683</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EB published with her name, through <NAME>Andrew Sowle</NAME>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Sayings of Women</TITLE>, a <TGENRE GENRENAME="ANTHOLOGY">collection</TGENRE> of scriptural excerpts designed to demonstrate that <TTHEMETOPIC>women</TTHEMETOPIC> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">receive an Office in the Truth as well as Men,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Sayings 23" DBREF="66546">23</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> a privilege entailing responsibility.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ESTC" DBREF="10912"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The full title is <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Sayings of Women, The">The Sayings of Women, Which were spoken upon sundry occasions, in several places of the Scriptures. Briefly Collected and set together to shew how the Lord poured out his Spirit upon the whole House of Israel; not only on the Male; but also on the Female; and made them Stewards of the manifold Gifts of his Grace; and as those who knew they must give an account of their Stewardship to the Lord</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ESTC" DBREF="10912"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION">A quotation follows: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">So did all the Women that were wise in Heart, manage their particular Talents, to the Praise and Glory of God.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Sayings title-page" DBREF="66546">title-page</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The collection begins with <TCHARACTERNAME>Sarah</TCHARACTERNAME>, wife of <TCHARACTERNAME>Abraham</TCHARACTERNAME>, and moves on through twenty-one listings of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">renowned</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Sayings 13" DBREF="66546">13</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TTHEMETOPIC><TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC" REG="Bible" REND="normal">Old Testament</TITLE> women</TTHEMETOPIC>. Each is introduced with the statement: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">We find . . . </QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Sayings passim" DBREF="66546">passim</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> EB&apos;s Old Testament examples bring her up to the mother of <NAME STANDARD="Solomon,, King of Israel">King Solomon</NAME>. Some items identify more than one woman speaker: <TCHARACTERNAME>Rachel</TCHARACTERNAME> and <TCHARACTERNAME>Leah</TCHARACTERNAME> share a single mention, as do the women who sang and danced before the victorious <NAME STANDARD="David,, King of Israel">David</NAME>. EB then moves on to the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">many Daughters</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Sayings 13" DBREF="66546">13</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC" REG="Bible" REND="normal">New Testament</TITLE> who <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">were made Heirs of the Grace of Life, together with their Brethren,</QUOTE> and who <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">spoke and praised the Lord.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Sayings 14" DBREF="66546">14</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The <NAME STANDARD="Mary,, the mother of Jesus">Virgin Mary</NAME> is fifth on this list At the end EB mentions a few more believing women in the New Testament for whom no sayings are recorded. She concludes by <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">laying down this assertion, viz. That as Male and Female are made one in Christ Jesus, so <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="rights of women">Women receive an Office in the Truth as well as Men</TMOTIF>, and they have a Stewardship, &amp; must give an account of their Stewardship to their Lord as well as the Men: Therefore they ought to be faithful to God, and valiant for his Truth upon the Earth.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Sayings 23" DBREF="66546">23</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In her last sentence EB looks forward to women receiving their accolade of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><EMPH>Well done, good and faithful Servants, enter into the undisturbed Rest and Joy of your Lord.</EMPH></QUOTE> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">She signs her name, then adds a postscript reminding her readers, with appropriate <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REND="normal">Bible</TITLE> texts, that although a woman, <TCHARACTERNAME>Eve</TCHARACTERNAME>, first brought sin into the world and with it death, it was also a woman who bore Christ and thus brought <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><EMPH>Reconciliation and Restoration.</EMPH></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bathurst, Sayings 24" DBREF="66546">24</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>A Collection</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66545" PLACEHOLDER="EB, Truth Vindicated, 1691"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>13 July 1691</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL"><RBESTKNOWNWORK><NAME>Tace Sowle</NAME>&apos;s first project on taking over her <NAME STANDARD="Sowle, Andrew">father</NAME>&apos;s publishing firm was for <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Truth Vindicated">Truth Vindicated by the Faithful Testimony and Writings of the Innocent Servant and Hand-Maid of the Lord, <NAME>Elizabeth Bathurst</NAME>, Deceased</TITLE>.</RBESTKNOWNWORK></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bracken and Silver 254" DBREF="6732">254</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ESTC" DBREF="10912"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS><RESEARCHNOTE>on her father&apos;s testimony 6 month = June.</RESEARCHNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME>Paula McDowell</NAME> records this business decision, taken some years (or possibly only some weeks) after EB&apos;s death. Tace Sowle specifically mentioned for inclusion Bathurst&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Sayings of Women</TITLE>, 1683, which appears in the collection along with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Expostulatory Appeal to the Professors of Christianity, An">An Expostulatory Appeal</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Truth&apos;s Vindication</TITLE>. The <ORGNAME STANDARD="Society of Friends" REG="Quakers">Society of Friends</ORGNAME> Morning Meeting agreed to the publication after Sowle had informed Bathurst&apos;s <NAME STANDARD="Bathurst, Charles">father</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Bathurst, Frances">mother</NAME>. The title of the collection is somewhat confusing&mdash;<TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Truth Vindicated</TITLE>, when Bathurst&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Truth&apos;s Vindication</TITLE>, 1679, is only one item in the new work, along with assertions of authenticity and celebration of EB by other hands. <PEDITIONS>The collection (whose title-page bears two biblical texts) was re-issued by the <ORGNAME>Sowle Press</ORGNAME> in at least six editions from 1695 to 1731. Others followed generations later, in 1773, 1774, and 1788.</PEDITIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bracken and Silver 254, 256" DBREF="6732">254, 256</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ESTC" DBREF="10912"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Although comparatively little is known of EB&apos;s life, <NAME>Luella M. Wright</NAME>, writing in the 1930s, took her as exemplifying the way Friends&apos; writings <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">contain a large percentage of material personal in nature.</QUOTE> She noted the large proportion of Bathurst&apos;s collection which is given to testimonies, and that her preface, her exhortation, and her transitions, all reflect her individuality.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wright 196" DBREF="66685">196</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC.</SOURCE><SOURCE>English Short Title Catalogue.</SOURCE><SOURCE>McDowell, Paula. in Bracken and Silver. DLB.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Wright, Luella M. The Literary Life of the Early Friends.</SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></WRITING>